WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.441 --> 00:00:03.108
(magical music)

2
00:00:07.980 --> 00:00:11.430
<v Dave>It is a pleasure to welcome Dr. Benjamin Gilmer.</v>

3
00:00:11.430 --> 00:00:13.320
Dr. Gilmer is the associate professor

4
00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:16.170
at the University of North Carolina School of Medicine.

5
00:00:16.170 --> 00:00:17.850
He is part of the MAHEC

6
00:00:17.850 --> 00:00:21.270
Family Medicine Residency in Asheville.

7
00:00:21.270 --> 00:00:24.780
He is going to be leading our conversation on urology.

8
00:00:24.780 --> 00:00:26.190
So Benjamin, thank you very much.

9
00:00:26.190 --> 00:00:28.590
Pleasure to see you, sir.
<v ->Thank you, Dave.</v>

10
00:00:28.590 --> 00:00:29.853
Good to be here.

11
00:00:30.870 --> 00:00:32.973
I have nothing to disclose.

12
00:00:34.020 --> 00:00:35.100
So today we're gonna take a look

13
00:00:35.100 --> 00:00:38.100
at some of the hallmark aspects

14
00:00:38.100 --> 00:00:41.550
of this caveman science of urology.

15
00:00:41.550 --> 00:00:46.550
We can all be a urologist in 28 minutes and 13 seconds.

16
00:00:47.550 --> 00:00:50.550
So we're gonna take a look at some of the aspects of BPH.

17
00:00:50.550 --> 00:00:52.170
We're gonna look at ED.

18
00:00:52.170 --> 00:00:56.790
We're gonna look at PSA and why Dr. Weissmiller's father

19
00:00:56.790 --> 00:01:00.210
should not have had a PC, PSA at age 90.

20
00:01:00.210 --> 00:01:02.723
And then we'll take a look at some kidney stones too.

21
00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:05.883
Starting off with a question.

22
00:01:07.560 --> 00:01:09.750
52-year-old male presents

23
00:01:09.750 --> 00:01:11.760
with evolving symptoms of nocturia.

24
00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:14.490
He notes an increase in dribbling following urination

25
00:01:14.490 --> 00:01:16.770
and less force of stream.

26
00:01:16.770 --> 00:01:18.450
Which of the following is the most appropriate

27
00:01:18.450 --> 00:01:21.603
first-line agent of treatment?

28
00:01:22.710 --> 00:01:23.823
Is it Cipro,

29
00:01:24.840 --> 00:01:25.863
Terazosin,

30
00:01:27.540 --> 00:01:28.743
Dutasteride,

31
00:01:30.240 --> 00:01:32.253
or Saw Palmetto?

32
00:01:38.820 --> 00:01:40.800
74%. That's a great start.

33
00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:43.140
So Terazosin, excellent.

34
00:01:43.140 --> 00:01:45.030
Let's dig into this a little bit more.

35
00:01:45.030 --> 00:01:49.230
BPH, as you have all encountered in your careers,

36
00:01:49.230 --> 00:01:51.840
is extremely prevalent.

37
00:01:51.840 --> 00:01:52.710
By the time you're 30,

38
00:01:52.710 --> 00:01:55.230
you have an eight to 10% chance of having it.

39
00:01:55.230 --> 00:01:58.620
By the time you're 80, you have an 80% chance of having BPH.

40
00:01:58.620 --> 00:02:00.150
So it's so common.

41
00:02:00.150 --> 00:02:01.290
It's a collaboration

42
00:02:01.290 --> 00:02:04.020
of the increased dynamic tension of the prostate

43
00:02:04.020 --> 00:02:06.120
and the increased volume of the prostate.

44
00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:08.763
Together, they equal BPH.

45
00:02:10.890 --> 00:02:13.230
The best way to sort of risk stratify

46
00:02:13.230 --> 00:02:15.047
where you are on the BPH spectrum

47
00:02:15.047 --> 00:02:17.968
is to take a look at the American Neurologic Association

48
00:02:17.968 --> 00:02:21.960
Symptom Scoring Index, which is the next slide.

49
00:02:21.960 --> 00:02:24.510
The symptoms have not changed

50
00:02:24.510 --> 00:02:26.580
since the last time you took a board exam.

51
00:02:26.580 --> 00:02:28.830
Decreased force of stream is in this patient,

52
00:02:28.830 --> 00:02:32.730
hesitancy, terminal dribbling, nocturia, et cetera.

53
00:02:32.730 --> 00:02:35.580
The reason why we're so concerned about BPH...

54
00:02:35.580 --> 00:02:38.550
A, there's a lot of morbidity associated with it,

55
00:02:38.550 --> 00:02:42.150
but the complications can ultimately lead to increased UTIs,

56
00:02:42.150 --> 00:02:46.290
hydronephrosis, and ultimately renal failure.

57
00:02:46.290 --> 00:02:49.770
So if you have a score that's greater than 20...

58
00:02:49.770 --> 00:02:51.360
So this is a good slide to circle,

59
00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:54.090
to come back to look at the hallmark features of BPH.

60
00:02:54.090 --> 00:02:55.590
If your score is greater than 20,

61
00:02:55.590 --> 00:02:59.550
that puts you in a severe category.

62
00:02:59.550 --> 00:03:01.620
So what are the risk factors?

63
00:03:01.620 --> 00:03:03.810
If you're older than 30,

64
00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:08.810
if you have even a slight drinking problem at night,

65
00:03:09.390 --> 00:03:12.150
that's not good for sleep, but it's also not good for BPH.

66
00:03:12.150 --> 00:03:16.020
Smoking, diabetes, insulin as a growth hormone

67
00:03:16.020 --> 00:03:20.400
affects all organ systems, including the prostate.

68
00:03:20.400 --> 00:03:23.523
Hypertension, obesity, and a sedentary lifestyle.

69
00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:28.510
So the medications have not really changed much either

70
00:03:28.510 --> 00:03:30.000
over the years.

71
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.060
There have been a few additional ones added, but overall,

72
00:03:33.060 --> 00:03:34.830
you have the Alpha-1 antagonists

73
00:03:34.830 --> 00:03:37.794
and you have the 5-Alpha reductase inhibitors.

74
00:03:37.794 --> 00:03:41.160
There's not a lot of difference in terms of efficacy

75
00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:43.890
between the five Alpha-1 antagonists.

76
00:03:43.890 --> 00:03:47.220
There are selective ones and there are non-selective ones.

77
00:03:47.220 --> 00:03:50.940
Terazosin and doxazosin are the non-selective ones.

78
00:03:50.940 --> 00:03:53.430
They can make your blood pressure go down

79
00:03:53.430 --> 00:03:57.694
more so than tamsulosin, Flomax.

80
00:03:57.694 --> 00:04:02.310
They all collaborate with decreasing the dynamic component

81
00:04:02.310 --> 00:04:04.931
in contrast with the 4-Alpha reductase inhibitors

82
00:04:04.931 --> 00:04:07.414
such as finasteride.

83
00:04:07.414 --> 00:04:10.380
This affects the size, right?

84
00:04:10.380 --> 00:04:14.340
Because it decreases the amount of testosterone

85
00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:17.157
that gets converted to DHT.

86
00:04:17.157 --> 00:04:18.910
DHT being the active metabolite

87
00:04:18.910 --> 00:04:21.660
that increases the size of the prostate.

88
00:04:21.660 --> 00:04:24.990
So overall, out of all of your testosterone,

89
00:04:24.990 --> 00:04:28.833
10% of that becomes, ultimately, DHT.

90
00:04:29.851 --> 00:04:33.030
And 5-Alpha reductase inhibitors block that.

91
00:04:33.030 --> 00:04:34.350
So what if your patient comes back

92
00:04:34.350 --> 00:04:38.197
and says after six months, "I don't believe this is working.

93
00:04:38.197 --> 00:04:41.160
The finasteride is not working."

94
00:04:41.160 --> 00:04:42.273
What do you tell them?

95
00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:48.270
Give it another six months because it can take up to a year

96
00:04:48.270 --> 00:04:50.490
for it to have full efficacy.

97
00:04:50.490 --> 00:04:54.093
The number needed to treat at a year is excellent, so two.

98
00:04:56.580 --> 00:05:00.663
So BPH medicines can be used in concert together.

99
00:05:01.590 --> 00:05:04.500
The 5-Alpha reductase inhibitors are the most effective

100
00:05:04.500 --> 00:05:06.420
if you have a large prostate.

101
00:05:06.420 --> 00:05:08.310
Now, how many of you can determine

102
00:05:08.310 --> 00:05:11.583
if one's prostate is greater than 30 CCs?

103
00:05:13.170 --> 00:05:16.200
I can't do that. Nobody can do that.

104
00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:17.790
Even the urologists are kidding themselves.

105
00:05:17.790 --> 00:05:19.500
It's a difficult exam,

106
00:05:19.500 --> 00:05:22.099
which is why we don't do them very frequently.

107
00:05:22.099 --> 00:05:24.630
And we have this beautiful thing called ultrasound

108
00:05:24.630 --> 00:05:28.786
that's really good at determining the size of your prostate.

109
00:05:28.786 --> 00:05:32.910
So that would be the best way to measure.

110
00:05:32.910 --> 00:05:35.970
And if you notice that your prostate size

111
00:05:35.970 --> 00:05:36.840
is greater than 30,

112
00:05:36.840 --> 00:05:39.930
then the 5-Alpha reductase inhibitors are great.

113
00:05:39.930 --> 00:05:43.980
If it's less than 30, they're much less effective.

114
00:05:43.980 --> 00:05:48.000
Saw palmetto, as in this question, is not effective.

115
00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.775
It is equal to placebo.

116
00:05:50.775 --> 00:05:52.627
How many of you have had patients who have told you,

117
00:05:52.627 --> 00:05:54.240
"Oh, it's saw palmetto."

118
00:05:54.240 --> 00:05:56.283
Yeah, it's equal to placebo.

119
00:05:57.480 --> 00:05:59.940
There are other treatments as well.

120
00:05:59.940 --> 00:06:01.680
Cialis has great data.

121
00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:06.420
In fact, Cialis versus Finasteride

122
00:06:06.420 --> 00:06:10.800
or the alpha antagonist are the same.

123
00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:13.980
So the efficacy is about the same.

124
00:06:13.980 --> 00:06:17.220
Outside of those three classes of medicines,

125
00:06:17.220 --> 00:06:19.440
there are a number of different treatments.

126
00:06:19.440 --> 00:06:21.360
The TURP being the gold standard.

127
00:06:21.360 --> 00:06:24.285
So that's the gold standard surgical treatment.

128
00:06:24.285 --> 00:06:25.620
There are others.

129
00:06:25.620 --> 00:06:27.870
There are the microwave thermotherapy treatments.

130
00:06:27.870 --> 00:06:32.430
There are the other incision-based treatments.

131
00:06:32.430 --> 00:06:35.103
None of them are as effective as a TURP.

132
00:06:36.060 --> 00:06:37.980
However, the side effects

133
00:06:37.980 --> 00:06:40.290
and the morbidity associated with the surgery

134
00:06:40.290 --> 00:06:41.550
is oftentimes better.

135
00:06:41.550 --> 00:06:44.128
So we hear a lot of people having like a lift surgery

136
00:06:44.128 --> 00:06:46.620
or an incision or a slit surgery.

137
00:06:46.620 --> 00:06:48.060
Those can be very effective,

138
00:06:48.060 --> 00:06:50.060
but the TURP is still the gold standard.

139
00:06:51.690 --> 00:06:52.680
So in all my slides,

140
00:06:52.680 --> 00:06:55.470
I'm gonna include practice recommendations for you.

141
00:06:55.470 --> 00:06:58.530
So put a big star on these.

142
00:06:58.530 --> 00:07:02.580
They kind of give the A evidence, A and B evidence

143
00:07:02.580 --> 00:07:05.973
and good slides to go back to do a quick review.

144
00:07:07.470 --> 00:07:10.680
Next question is a 70-year-old male

145
00:07:10.680 --> 00:07:14.160
who presents with dysuria, polyuria, urgency,

146
00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:18.750
incomplete voiding and suprapubic pain for several days.

147
00:07:18.750 --> 00:07:22.530
On exam, his prostate is tender, enlarged, and boggy.

148
00:07:22.530 --> 00:07:26.610
You diagnose him with acute bacterial prostatitis, ABP.

149
00:07:26.610 --> 00:07:28.860
All the following risk factors

150
00:07:28.860 --> 00:07:31.590
increase the risk of a poor prognosis with ABP

151
00:07:31.590 --> 00:07:34.740
in his age group except...

152
00:07:34.740 --> 00:07:35.793
History of BPH,

153
00:07:36.840 --> 00:07:39.240
a BMI greater than 25,

154
00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:43.233
a fever, or urinary retention?

155
00:07:48.930 --> 00:07:51.570
So the except answer is BMI.

156
00:07:51.570 --> 00:07:55.689
All these other things do contribute to a greater risk

157
00:07:55.689 --> 00:07:58.953
of sequelae associated with the acute bacterial prostatitis.

158
00:08:01.920 --> 00:08:03.330
So acute bacterial prostatitis,

159
00:08:03.330 --> 00:08:06.420
there's sort of a bimodal incidence between 20 and 40

160
00:08:06.420 --> 00:08:08.070
and then greater than 70.

161
00:08:08.070 --> 00:08:10.980
This is the opportunity to do a rectal exam

162
00:08:10.980 --> 00:08:13.890
to determine if it's warm, tender and boggy.

163
00:08:13.890 --> 00:08:16.290
That's still very appropriate for a rectal exam.

164
00:08:17.130 --> 00:08:21.090
The ultimate goal is to determine the pathogen.

165
00:08:21.090 --> 00:08:23.583
So getting a culture or urine culture, et cetera.

166
00:08:24.477 --> 00:08:27.630
The symptoms as in this patient are classic.

167
00:08:27.630 --> 00:08:30.540
They're irritative, obstructive symptoms.

168
00:08:30.540 --> 00:08:34.702
You can have suprapubic pain, you can have rectal pain,

169
00:08:34.702 --> 00:08:36.930
you can have painful ejaculation,

170
00:08:36.930 --> 00:08:39.570
but be careful for the systemic one.

171
00:08:39.570 --> 00:08:41.070
So the systemic symptoms are the ones

172
00:08:41.070 --> 00:08:43.170
that are the most critical to identify

173
00:08:43.170 --> 00:08:46.800
because ABP can evolve into a septic picture.

174
00:08:46.800 --> 00:08:49.320
So be careful with that.

175
00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:50.869
When you're thinking about the differential,

176
00:08:50.869 --> 00:08:53.767
BPH is on the list, of course.

177
00:08:53.767 --> 00:08:57.360
Chronic bacterial prostatitis and the key word there

178
00:08:57.360 --> 00:08:59.073
is greater than three months.

179
00:09:00.330 --> 00:09:01.950
Chronic pelvic pain syndrome

180
00:09:01.950 --> 00:09:06.390
where there's no identifiable infection present,

181
00:09:06.390 --> 00:09:09.540
and then run-of-the-mill cystitis as well.

182
00:09:09.540 --> 00:09:11.940
So those are all on the differential.

183
00:09:11.940 --> 00:09:13.800
Treatment has not changed much

184
00:09:13.800 --> 00:09:15.833
except that you need to know

185
00:09:15.833 --> 00:09:20.010
what are the pathogens in your region

186
00:09:20.010 --> 00:09:22.560
and what are the resistance patterns in your region.

187
00:09:22.560 --> 00:09:24.840
So E coli is still big player,

188
00:09:24.840 --> 00:09:27.563
gram-negative enterics, still big players.

189
00:09:27.563 --> 00:09:31.440
Know what your pathogens are in their resistance patterns

190
00:09:31.440 --> 00:09:33.003
just as you would for UTI.

191
00:09:33.840 --> 00:09:35.580
If it's a mild case of ABP,

192
00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:38.940
10 to 14 days is appropriate duration of therapy.

193
00:09:38.940 --> 00:09:42.783
If it's more severe, then you're gonna treat for four weeks.

194
00:09:45.330 --> 00:09:47.130
So there are lots of reasons

195
00:09:47.130 --> 00:09:52.050
to have lower-urinary-tract symptoms besides BPH.

196
00:09:52.050 --> 00:09:55.101
So just to keep this in mind, there are anatomic reasons,

197
00:09:55.101 --> 00:09:59.640
other types of infections, UTIs, et cetera.

198
00:09:59.640 --> 00:10:00.960
Inflammatory conditions

199
00:10:00.960 --> 00:10:04.170
like the chronic pelvic pain syndrome,

200
00:10:04.170 --> 00:10:05.370
the malignancy issues.

201
00:10:05.370 --> 00:10:06.960
Don't forget the malignancy issues.

202
00:10:06.960 --> 00:10:10.292
And then all sorts of medications that we know

203
00:10:10.292 --> 00:10:12.780
that have been referred to already today,

204
00:10:12.780 --> 00:10:16.920
namely the anticholinergics, the Beers medications,

205
00:10:16.920 --> 00:10:20.430
antihistamines, beta agonists as well.

206
00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:23.730
Opioids, you may see this with your chronic opioid patients,

207
00:10:23.730 --> 00:10:26.400
have have lower-urinary-tract symptoms.

208
00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:28.680
And then TCAs because they ultimately

209
00:10:28.680 --> 00:10:30.960
have strong anticholinergic properties.

210
00:10:30.960 --> 00:10:35.043
And then there are the neurologic conditions to not forget.

211
00:10:36.870 --> 00:10:39.153
Next question.

212
00:10:40.440 --> 00:10:43.470
62-year-old male presents with ED

213
00:10:43.470 --> 00:10:46.230
and increased fatigue for six months.

214
00:10:46.230 --> 00:10:47.880
His past medical history is significant

215
00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:51.480
for obstructive sleep apnea and BPH.

216
00:10:51.480 --> 00:10:54.900
On exam, you notice decreased muscle mass and thinning hair.

217
00:10:54.900 --> 00:10:58.533
What is the most appropriate next diagnostic step?

218
00:10:59.520 --> 00:11:00.663
Do you check an LH?

219
00:11:01.889 --> 00:11:03.139
Do you check a prolactin?

220
00:11:04.050 --> 00:11:06.783
Do you check an early-morning testosterone?

221
00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:10.863
Or do you check a scrotal ultrasound?

222
00:11:16.260 --> 00:11:17.093
Good. 90.

223
00:11:17.093 --> 00:11:20.970
We're getting closer to Dr. Gary's goal. 92%.

224
00:11:20.970 --> 00:11:23.400
Yes, you got that diagnosis right.

225
00:11:23.400 --> 00:11:25.053
So this is hypogonadism.

226
00:11:26.130 --> 00:11:29.253
Classic symptoms that you know already.

227
00:11:31.140 --> 00:11:34.530
The question is, what type of hypogonadism is this?

228
00:11:34.530 --> 00:11:37.500
Is it a primary or is it a secondary type?

229
00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:40.983
And so this patient likely had low testosterone.

230
00:11:42.600 --> 00:11:45.990
And again, low testosterone can be best evaluated

231
00:11:45.990 --> 00:11:48.600
between 7:00 AM and 10:00 PM.

232
00:11:48.600 --> 00:11:52.680
That's where the maximum level of testosterone is.

233
00:11:52.680 --> 00:11:57.210
If you have a low T and a high FSH and LH,

234
00:11:57.210 --> 00:11:59.400
that tells you that the circuitry is intact,

235
00:11:59.400 --> 00:12:01.740
that the pituitary gland is working.

236
00:12:01.740 --> 00:12:04.230
So that will be a primary problem,

237
00:12:04.230 --> 00:12:06.750
a problem with the pump itself.

238
00:12:06.750 --> 00:12:10.260
In contrast to a low T with a low FSH and LH,

239
00:12:10.260 --> 00:12:12.390
that tells you something is going on

240
00:12:12.390 --> 00:12:17.130
with the HPA axis.

241
00:12:17.130 --> 00:12:19.950
So in that case, you need to consider MRI.

242
00:12:19.950 --> 00:12:21.990
You need to think about the other hormones

243
00:12:21.990 --> 00:12:23.250
that we'll talk about tomorrow

244
00:12:23.250 --> 00:12:25.770
that are associated with the pituitary gland,

245
00:12:25.770 --> 00:12:28.923
checking a T4, TSH and a prolactin.

246
00:12:31.440 --> 00:12:33.810
This is a good one to go back to,

247
00:12:33.810 --> 00:12:35.700
just thinking about all the different reasons

248
00:12:35.700 --> 00:12:36.930
to have a primary problem,

249
00:12:36.930 --> 00:12:38.580
which could be an infiltrated problem,

250
00:12:38.580 --> 00:12:40.020
it could be a traumatic problem,

251
00:12:40.020 --> 00:12:42.220
it could be a drug problem, all these things

252
00:12:43.860 --> 00:12:45.300
compared to a secondary problem,

253
00:12:45.300 --> 00:12:50.300
which would be the pituitary tumor, the micro adenoma,

254
00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:55.520
the inflammatory process, the Kallmann's process.

255
00:12:56.100 --> 00:13:00.990
Kallmann's disease, which is a problem with GnRH

256
00:13:00.990 --> 00:13:03.840
that didn't form properly during puberty.

257
00:13:03.840 --> 00:13:05.670
It is also the one that you may remember

258
00:13:05.670 --> 00:13:07.020
where you can't smell.

259
00:13:07.020 --> 00:13:10.050
There's the anosmia associated with Kallmann's syndrome.

260
00:13:10.050 --> 00:13:11.520
That's sort of a classic.

261
00:13:11.520 --> 00:13:15.390
And then HIV can also contribute to secondary causes.

262
00:13:15.390 --> 00:13:17.820
And you can have enzymatic problems.

263
00:13:17.820 --> 00:13:21.810
So this is where the 5-Alpha reductase enzyme itself

264
00:13:21.810 --> 00:13:23.700
has a relative deficiency.

265
00:13:23.700 --> 00:13:27.090
And so that doesn't enable testosterone

266
00:13:27.090 --> 00:13:30.750
to be converted to its active metabolite, DHT.

267
00:13:30.750 --> 00:13:33.720
Or you could even have a problem with the receptor.

268
00:13:33.720 --> 00:13:38.070
So the DHT does not interface well with the actual receptor.

269
00:13:38.070 --> 00:13:40.740
So you can have multiple areas

270
00:13:40.740 --> 00:13:43.590
where you can have hypogonadism,

271
00:13:43.590 --> 00:13:46.050
just thinking about that whole picture.

272
00:13:46.050 --> 00:13:48.600
So this is one where they're usually questions.

273
00:13:48.600 --> 00:13:51.990
Like, when is it appropriate to treat?

274
00:13:51.990 --> 00:13:54.263
When is it not appropriate to treat?

275
00:13:54.263 --> 00:13:57.210
Because everybody wants to be treated.

276
00:13:57.210 --> 00:14:00.030
And so the the primary goal

277
00:14:00.030 --> 00:14:03.300
is to restore sexual function overall,

278
00:14:03.300 --> 00:14:05.523
libido, well-being, and behavior.

279
00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:11.310
Don't forget that hypogonadism can lead to increased risk

280
00:14:11.310 --> 00:14:16.310
of bone density issues, growth hormone issues,

281
00:14:16.590 --> 00:14:19.770
and ultimately cardiovascular issues.

282
00:14:19.770 --> 00:14:21.540
If you have a metabolic syndrome

283
00:14:21.540 --> 00:14:24.513
that's a consequence of low testosterone.

284
00:14:27.870 --> 00:14:29.180
Replacement.

285
00:14:29.180 --> 00:14:31.770
No new information here,

286
00:14:31.770 --> 00:14:33.600
but there's one important thing to remember,

287
00:14:33.600 --> 00:14:37.320
is that whether you're replacing with IM injections

288
00:14:37.320 --> 00:14:39.840
or transdermal replacement,

289
00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:44.820
the efficacy and the ultimate result is gonna be the same.

290
00:14:44.820 --> 00:14:47.523
It's just a lot cheaper of course to use IM.

291
00:14:48.840 --> 00:14:50.130
If you wanna improve fertility,

292
00:14:50.130 --> 00:14:55.130
then you can jump into the hCG, hMG and GnRH.

293
00:14:55.470 --> 00:14:59.160
Probably unlikely to have a board-exam question

294
00:14:59.160 --> 00:15:01.353
regarding GnRH or hCG.

295
00:15:04.980 --> 00:15:08.520
So there are contraindications to testosterone,

296
00:15:08.520 --> 00:15:11.158
and in elderly population,

297
00:15:11.158 --> 00:15:15.570
those folks who are asking to be treated...

298
00:15:15.570 --> 00:15:17.880
Really, if you're gonna initiate treatment,

299
00:15:17.880 --> 00:15:21.030
they need to have an ultra-low testosterone.

300
00:15:21.030 --> 00:15:24.610
If you have a testosterone that's like say 400 to 600

301
00:15:25.920 --> 00:15:28.410
and they're having all these symptoms,

302
00:15:28.410 --> 00:15:31.110
the likelihood of the benefit of the testosterone

303
00:15:31.110 --> 00:15:32.280
is pretty low.

304
00:15:32.280 --> 00:15:35.300
So low, meaning less than 300 deciliters per...

305
00:15:41.460 --> 00:15:43.320
Nanograms per deciliter.

306
00:15:43.320 --> 00:15:45.690
Also important to know what your hospital,

307
00:15:45.690 --> 00:15:48.150
how they report their testosterones.

308
00:15:48.150 --> 00:15:52.200
Normally, it's gonna be in nanoliters...

309
00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:54.123
Nanograms per deciliter.

310
00:15:54.960 --> 00:15:57.060
But if you have prostate cancer or breast cancer,

311
00:15:57.060 --> 00:15:58.653
that's an absolute contraindication.

312
00:15:58.653 --> 00:16:02.280
It's a relative contraindication if you have BPH

313
00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:05.220
or if you've had a known prostate nodule before

314
00:16:05.220 --> 00:16:09.150
or erythrocytosis, or heart failure.

315
00:16:09.150 --> 00:16:11.310
Sleep apnea, gynecomastia, VTE,

316
00:16:11.310 --> 00:16:14.790
those are also relative contraindications.

317
00:16:14.790 --> 00:16:18.780
So testosterone brings with it risk as well.

318
00:16:18.780 --> 00:16:21.720
So here are your practice recommendations.

319
00:16:21.720 --> 00:16:22.950
Again, testosterone therapy

320
00:16:22.950 --> 00:16:25.233
leads to small improvements in ED.

321
00:16:27.420 --> 00:16:31.005
And if you treat someone with testosterone

322
00:16:31.005 --> 00:16:36.005
and we'll just say there the testosterone is 300 to 350,

323
00:16:36.510 --> 00:16:40.650
and you treat them and their ED doesn't get better,

324
00:16:40.650 --> 00:16:42.300
then really there's no benefit

325
00:16:42.300 --> 00:16:45.090
to continuing therapy at that point,

326
00:16:45.090 --> 00:16:48.390
unless they have profound metabolic syndrome, et cetera.

327
00:16:48.390 --> 00:16:50.520
Here's a younger person, a 46-year-old male,

328
00:16:50.520 --> 00:16:52.620
who comes in with worsening ED.

329
00:16:52.620 --> 00:16:55.078
He denies history of depression, anxiety,

330
00:16:55.078 --> 00:16:57.690
CAD or peripheral vascular disease.

331
00:16:57.690 --> 00:17:01.830
His BMI is 32, he exercises three times a week.

332
00:17:01.830 --> 00:17:05.370
A recent AM testosterone level was 310.

333
00:17:05.370 --> 00:17:08.730
Which of the following is the most appropriate step?

334
00:17:08.730 --> 00:17:10.023
Testosterone gel,

335
00:17:11.610 --> 00:17:12.573
Trazodone,

336
00:17:13.654 --> 00:17:16.080
a phosphodiesterase inhibitor,

337
00:17:16.080 --> 00:17:17.703
or yohimbine?

338
00:17:23.760 --> 00:17:25.790
70%. So...

339
00:17:27.060 --> 00:17:28.800
This is a good illustration, again,

340
00:17:28.800 --> 00:17:32.850
of if you have a mild to moderately low testosterone.

341
00:17:32.850 --> 00:17:36.400
The likelihood of testosterone supplementation

342
00:17:37.260 --> 00:17:39.923
benefiting that person is much less likely

343
00:17:39.923 --> 00:17:41.820
than using Viagra.

344
00:17:41.820 --> 00:17:43.863
So that's why this answer is C,

345
00:17:44.760 --> 00:17:47.160
a phosphodiesterase inhibitor.

346
00:17:47.160 --> 00:17:51.750
Keep in mind that ED is equal to small vessel disease.

347
00:17:51.750 --> 00:17:53.820
So the hazard ratios are pretty significant.

348
00:17:53.820 --> 00:17:56.940
So with these patients, please make that association

349
00:17:56.940 --> 00:17:59.130
that there's increased risk of mortality

350
00:17:59.130 --> 00:18:02.073
and cardiovascular events associated with the ED.

351
00:18:04.140 --> 00:18:07.020
The phosphodiesterase inhibitors are very, very effective.

352
00:18:07.020 --> 00:18:09.330
So number needed to treat, only two.

353
00:18:09.330 --> 00:18:12.870
They work especially well with folks who have diabetes,

354
00:18:12.870 --> 00:18:16.530
spinal cord dysfunction, and of course SSRIs.

355
00:18:16.530 --> 00:18:17.670
Very helpful.

356
00:18:17.670 --> 00:18:19.200
They can be helpful also

357
00:18:19.200 --> 00:18:21.513
in the nerve sparing prostatectomies.

358
00:18:22.890 --> 00:18:24.900
And overall, the efficacy

359
00:18:24.900 --> 00:18:28.440
amongst all of the phosphodiesterase inhibitors

360
00:18:28.440 --> 00:18:30.930
are fairly similar.

361
00:18:30.930 --> 00:18:32.880
Dropout rates are a little bit diminished

362
00:18:32.880 --> 00:18:35.103
or decreased with sildenafil.

363
00:18:36.180 --> 00:18:38.583
There are negative consequences though.

364
00:18:39.540 --> 00:18:41.850
Visual disturbances can happen.

365
00:18:41.850 --> 00:18:43.830
Priapism, especially with those folks

366
00:18:43.830 --> 00:18:45.630
who are already on Trazodone.

367
00:18:45.630 --> 00:18:48.963
Trazodone, which does not benefit ED greatly.

368
00:18:50.070 --> 00:18:53.400
Angina and even some central neural hearing loss

369
00:18:53.400 --> 00:18:57.180
can be associated with with phosphodiesterase inhibitors.

370
00:18:57.180 --> 00:19:00.183
Here are all the other ED treatments.

371
00:19:02.130 --> 00:19:04.980
Again, the testosterone, only if it's ultra low

372
00:19:04.980 --> 00:19:06.600
will be beneficial.

373
00:19:06.600 --> 00:19:08.940
There is actually good data for all these others.

374
00:19:08.940 --> 00:19:13.560
Alprostadil, less preferred mechanism, it's the injection.

375
00:19:13.560 --> 00:19:17.130
Yohimbine surprisingly does have some data to support it,

376
00:19:17.130 --> 00:19:19.980
but it's much less potent than the others.

377
00:19:19.980 --> 00:19:22.200
Vacuuming devices also have data.

378
00:19:22.200 --> 00:19:25.710
Trazodone, and this can come up on board exams,

379
00:19:25.710 --> 00:19:29.280
may worsen ED, so it is not beneficial,

380
00:19:29.280 --> 00:19:30.150
it may actually worsen

381
00:19:30.150 --> 00:19:32.910
and that is the true also with the fibrates.

382
00:19:32.910 --> 00:19:34.650
So be careful with fibrates,

383
00:19:34.650 --> 00:19:38.100
even statins can potentially make ED worse.

384
00:19:38.100 --> 00:19:41.033
And of course, being on the obesity curve,

385
00:19:41.033 --> 00:19:44.670
also there is a linear relationship with obesity.

386
00:19:44.670 --> 00:19:49.110
So lifestyle-management issues are also very important.

387
00:19:49.110 --> 00:19:52.200
Here are your practice recommendations.

388
00:19:52.200 --> 00:19:54.750
Don't forget the psychosocial elements of ED.

389
00:19:54.750 --> 00:19:56.523
That's a big component as well.

390
00:19:57.930 --> 00:20:01.500
61-year-old male comes in for a routine physical

391
00:20:01.500 --> 00:20:02.880
requesting your blessing

392
00:20:02.880 --> 00:20:05.640
to perform a PSA for prostate cancer.

393
00:20:05.640 --> 00:20:07.260
He denies any symptoms at the time

394
00:20:07.260 --> 00:20:09.365
and he doesn't have any prostate cancer history.

395
00:20:09.365 --> 00:20:12.510
What would you recommend this person?

396
00:20:12.510 --> 00:20:15.483
Would you recommend a routine screening at 60?

397
00:20:16.740 --> 00:20:21.740
Would you recommend a 55 to 69 against screening with PSA,

398
00:20:22.500 --> 00:20:26.760
or per the USPSTF, this is an I recommendation.

399
00:20:26.760 --> 00:20:30.540
Or, per the USPSTF, this is a C recommendation

400
00:20:30.540 --> 00:20:33.120
between 55 and 69.

401
00:20:33.120 --> 00:20:35.013
So merits a conversation.

402
00:20:36.270 --> 00:20:37.953
This gentleman is 61.

403
00:20:43.140 --> 00:20:46.140
Learning opportunity here.

404
00:20:46.140 --> 00:20:47.670
So we'll jump into this.

405
00:20:47.670 --> 00:20:50.580
So the correct answer is D.

406
00:20:50.580 --> 00:20:53.250
Between the ages of 55 and 69,

407
00:20:53.250 --> 00:20:54.750
the USPSTF recommends

408
00:20:54.750 --> 00:20:58.830
that there should be a conversation had with your patient.

409
00:20:58.830 --> 00:21:00.280
So let's take a look at this.

410
00:21:01.120 --> 00:21:05.760
Here is the USPSTF initial recommendation in 2017

411
00:21:05.760 --> 00:21:08.760
where they recommended a C recommendation.

412
00:21:08.760 --> 00:21:13.140
In 2018, the following year, the AFP jumped on board

413
00:21:13.140 --> 00:21:15.180
with this recommendation as well,

414
00:21:15.180 --> 00:21:16.920
saying that it's a C recommendation,

415
00:21:16.920 --> 00:21:18.993
that there should be a conversation.

416
00:21:19.890 --> 00:21:24.890
If you are 70 or above, as in Dr. Weissmiller's father,

417
00:21:25.410 --> 00:21:26.910
this is a D recommendation.

418
00:21:26.910 --> 00:21:29.040
Do not do.

419
00:21:29.040 --> 00:21:30.270
And when you break down the data,

420
00:21:30.270 --> 00:21:32.250
and this is a conversation we've had

421
00:21:32.250 --> 00:21:35.590
with all of our male patients at some time,

422
00:21:35.590 --> 00:21:38.730
the numbers are a little bit squishy, but overall,

423
00:21:38.730 --> 00:21:41.700
if you have 1,000 patient, 1,000 men

424
00:21:41.700 --> 00:21:43.470
and you screen them with a PSA

425
00:21:43.470 --> 00:21:47.250
and 240 of them come back positive,

426
00:21:47.250 --> 00:21:51.600
out of those 240, 80 have positive biopsies.

427
00:21:51.600 --> 00:21:55.770
Out of those 80 positive biopsies who go to surgery,

428
00:21:55.770 --> 00:21:59.610
there is one to two lives that are spared

429
00:21:59.610 --> 00:22:01.290
out of 1,000 people.

430
00:22:01.290 --> 00:22:03.000
And there's considerable morbidity

431
00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:04.680
associated with the surgery.

432
00:22:04.680 --> 00:22:06.600
So that is the data.

433
00:22:06.600 --> 00:22:09.987
That is why this is a D recommendation after 70

434
00:22:09.987 --> 00:22:13.473
and a C recommendation between 55 and 69.

435
00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:17.040
This is a very common question.

436
00:22:17.040 --> 00:22:20.640
So here's a 49-year-old who comes in with recurrent episodes

437
00:22:20.640 --> 00:22:23.100
of hematuria and flank pain.

438
00:22:23.100 --> 00:22:25.440
A spiral CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis

439
00:22:25.440 --> 00:22:28.153
reveals a kidney stone.

440
00:22:28.153 --> 00:22:32.130
Eventually she passes the stone into her urinary strainer

441
00:22:32.130 --> 00:22:33.480
and the analysis of the stone

442
00:22:33.480 --> 00:22:36.570
reveals a calcium oxalate stone.

443
00:22:36.570 --> 00:22:40.770
So what kind of dietary recommendation would you make?

444
00:22:40.770 --> 00:22:43.020
Would you tell them to decrease their calcium

445
00:22:44.010 --> 00:22:47.490
or would you say it's okay to have a normal calcium diet?

446
00:22:47.490 --> 00:22:49.900
Or would you ask them to decrease their fiber

447
00:22:51.150 --> 00:22:56.150
or to decrease their vitamin C that they're taking?

448
00:23:01.890 --> 00:23:03.243
Good. Good, good, good.

449
00:23:04.920 --> 00:23:07.500
A normal calcium diet would be the recommendation.

450
00:23:07.500 --> 00:23:11.163
So decreasing calcium doesn't make much of a difference.

451
00:23:12.030 --> 00:23:15.570
Decreasing fiber makes a difference

452
00:23:15.570 --> 00:23:19.953
and decreasing natural forms of citrate make a difference,

453
00:23:20.850 --> 00:23:22.110
or don't make a difference.

454
00:23:22.110 --> 00:23:25.050
So basically, for a calcium stone,

455
00:23:25.050 --> 00:23:27.390
the things that contribute to a calcium stone

456
00:23:27.390 --> 00:23:29.610
are the amount of calcium

457
00:23:29.610 --> 00:23:32.970
that's circulating through the nephron

458
00:23:32.970 --> 00:23:35.130
and the status of the pH.

459
00:23:35.130 --> 00:23:37.620
So presence of calcium, high.

460
00:23:37.620 --> 00:23:42.620
High pHs favor the formation of of calcium phosphate stones,

461
00:23:44.580 --> 00:23:46.323
which would be the most common.

462
00:23:47.310 --> 00:23:50.040
So here are your risk factors if you're a male.

463
00:23:50.040 --> 00:23:53.280
If you are 65 or above,

464
00:23:53.280 --> 00:23:55.380
if you're chronically dehydrated,

465
00:23:55.380 --> 00:23:58.410
if you live where I do, in North Carolina,

466
00:23:58.410 --> 00:24:03.330
in the sweet tea belt, geography is important.

467
00:24:03.330 --> 00:24:05.610
If you have a family history,

468
00:24:05.610 --> 00:24:09.360
if you have high levels of dietary sodium,

469
00:24:09.360 --> 00:24:12.420
which is also a part of our sweet tea belt,

470
00:24:12.420 --> 00:24:15.540
and certain medications, which we'll talk about.

471
00:24:15.540 --> 00:24:18.233
The symptoms, I don't think we need to review for you.

472
00:24:19.380 --> 00:24:22.290
But here are the meds that can favor stone formation.

473
00:24:22.290 --> 00:24:26.643
So triamterene and sulfonamides, due to their solubility.

474
00:24:28.770 --> 00:24:32.310
Massively increased amounts of calcium and vitamin D

475
00:24:32.310 --> 00:24:33.540
that increased the amount of calcium

476
00:24:33.540 --> 00:24:35.050
flowing through the nephron.

477
00:24:36.150 --> 00:24:38.760
The carbonic anhydrase inhibitors

478
00:24:38.760 --> 00:24:41.530
which increase urinary pH

479
00:24:42.690 --> 00:24:45.360
in contrast with the citrate like the vitamin C,

480
00:24:45.360 --> 00:24:47.703
which decreases your pH.

481
00:24:49.110 --> 00:24:50.652
Certain protease inhibitors.

482
00:24:50.652 --> 00:24:53.070
And this is one to always remember,

483
00:24:53.070 --> 00:24:55.230
but not hydrochlorothiazide.

484
00:24:55.230 --> 00:24:56.063
And you'll see.

485
00:24:56.063 --> 00:24:57.390
We'll talk about hydrochlorothiazide again,

486
00:24:57.390 --> 00:25:02.390
but hydrochlorothiazide reabsorbs calcium in the nephron

487
00:25:03.290 --> 00:25:05.700
so it decreases the amount of calcium

488
00:25:05.700 --> 00:25:06.850
that's passing through,

489
00:25:08.760 --> 00:25:10.380
in contrast with gout,

490
00:25:10.380 --> 00:25:13.020
which we'll talk about in a little bit.

491
00:25:13.020 --> 00:25:15.840
So where do you go to first

492
00:25:15.840 --> 00:25:18.003
in terms of imaging options?

493
00:25:18.870 --> 00:25:21.300
If you have someone with a known stone already,

494
00:25:21.300 --> 00:25:25.380
just get an X-ray, 'cause you know it could be there.

495
00:25:25.380 --> 00:25:28.560
If you're pregnant or have other gallbladder related issues,

496
00:25:28.560 --> 00:25:30.210
get an ultrasound.

497
00:25:30.210 --> 00:25:32.460
You don't always see the stone with ultrasound,

498
00:25:32.460 --> 00:25:35.580
but you can see hydronephrosis with ultrasound.

499
00:25:35.580 --> 00:25:37.380
But gold standard with everybody else

500
00:25:37.380 --> 00:25:41.943
is to get a spiral CT, a non-contrast spiral CT.

501
00:25:43.080 --> 00:25:45.210
So this is a situation where size does matter.

502
00:25:45.210 --> 00:25:49.560
So less than four, almost all those will pass.

503
00:25:49.560 --> 00:25:51.690
They will almost always pass.

504
00:25:51.690 --> 00:25:56.580
And good to remember that the expulsion therapy

505
00:25:56.580 --> 00:25:59.880
such as an alpha blocker or tamsulosin,

506
00:25:59.880 --> 00:26:02.550
really has no benefit with a small stone.

507
00:26:02.550 --> 00:26:05.280
So less than four, don't give them Flomax.

508
00:26:05.280 --> 00:26:06.780
It's not helpful.

509
00:26:06.780 --> 00:26:10.020
If they have a larger stone between five and 10,

510
00:26:10.020 --> 00:26:13.320
then expulsion therapy with an alpha blocker,

511
00:26:13.320 --> 00:26:18.320
nifedipine or tamsulosin is effective.

512
00:26:18.390 --> 00:26:20.100
Still, in the five to 10 range,

513
00:26:20.100 --> 00:26:22.320
half of those stones will pass on their own.

514
00:26:22.320 --> 00:26:24.587
If they don't pass, then you need to consider

515
00:26:24.587 --> 00:26:29.587
getting your friendly urologists on board.

516
00:26:30.030 --> 00:26:32.280
Here are your practice recommendations for those.

517
00:26:32.280 --> 00:26:36.060
Again, the alpha blockers are the first choice

518
00:26:36.060 --> 00:26:39.873
for medical expulsion therapy in that five to 10 range.

519
00:26:41.070 --> 00:26:43.380
Don't forget the importance of hydration.

520
00:26:43.380 --> 00:26:45.975
And then if you have recurrent stones,

521
00:26:45.975 --> 00:26:48.453
please put them on a thiazide if possible.

522
00:26:49.740 --> 00:26:50.573
Last question.

523
00:26:50.573 --> 00:26:53.580
This is a 55-year-old who's noted to have kidney stones

524
00:26:53.580 --> 00:26:55.050
on plain films.

525
00:26:55.050 --> 00:26:57.364
He denies any pain at the time,

526
00:26:57.364 --> 00:26:59.850
no vomiting or bowel changes.

527
00:26:59.850 --> 00:27:02.700
Abdominal exam is overall unremarkable.

528
00:27:02.700 --> 00:27:05.073
So what do you do next?

529
00:27:06.420 --> 00:27:09.630
Do you get the urologist on board to break it up?

530
00:27:09.630 --> 00:27:11.913
Do you do an an ERCP?

531
00:27:13.350 --> 00:27:15.850
Do you watch patiently

532
00:27:17.326 --> 00:27:19.503
or do you pursue lithotripsy?

533
00:27:25.080 --> 00:27:27.196
Oh, we shattered Dr. Gary!

534
00:27:27.196 --> 00:27:28.050
(audience applauding)

535
00:27:28.050 --> 00:27:28.883
Yes.

536
00:27:29.850 --> 00:27:32.850
Please, no one else vote.
(audience laughing)

537
00:27:32.850 --> 00:27:34.413
We're gonna watchfully wait.

538
00:27:35.760 --> 00:27:39.690
One last slide on what do we do about hematospermia.

539
00:27:39.690 --> 00:27:42.870
Most of the time hematospermia resolves on its own.

540
00:27:42.870 --> 00:27:45.090
Most of the time it's related to one of these things,

541
00:27:45.090 --> 00:27:47.520
either a biopsy or a radiation.

542
00:27:47.520 --> 00:27:49.712
It can happen sporadically.

543
00:27:49.712 --> 00:27:53.280
We have seen these questions on the board exam.

544
00:27:53.280 --> 00:27:54.390
Think about these things.

545
00:27:54.390 --> 00:27:58.828
STIs, infection, prostatitis, maybe cancer.

546
00:27:58.828 --> 00:28:01.830
Frequent daily ejaculation can do it.

547
00:28:01.830 --> 00:28:03.690
And then if you live in Tanzania,

548
00:28:03.690 --> 00:28:08.250
schistosomiasis is a common culprit

549
00:28:08.250 --> 00:28:10.383
for sporadic hematospermia.

550
00:28:12.120 --> 00:28:13.920
Most of the time you could just wait.

551
00:28:13.920 --> 00:28:17.430
If the symptoms are persistent for more than a month,

552
00:28:17.430 --> 00:28:18.900
then you need to do something about it.

553
00:28:18.900 --> 00:28:21.733
You need to either look with an ultrasound...

554
00:28:21.733 --> 00:28:23.550
If you can't do that, then get an MRI,

555
00:28:23.550 --> 00:28:25.770
which is okay for second line.

556
00:28:25.770 --> 00:28:27.390
Make sure they don't have an infection.

557
00:28:27.390 --> 00:28:29.730
Rule out prostatitis.

558
00:28:29.730 --> 00:28:31.710
Don't get a PSA

559
00:28:31.710 --> 00:28:35.670
and give them reassurance for the most part

560
00:28:35.670 --> 00:28:38.700
because it's gonna get better, for the most part.

561
00:28:38.700 --> 00:28:41.100
There is some new merging data with Finasteride.

562
00:28:41.100 --> 00:28:43.200
We'll see how that pans out

563
00:28:43.200 --> 00:28:46.350
for patients who have refractory symptoms.

564
00:28:46.350 --> 00:28:48.510
And there are some other supplementary slides

565
00:28:48.510 --> 00:28:50.622
that you might want to take a look at later

566
00:28:50.622 --> 00:28:55.622
that look at some of the other elements of urology

567
00:28:55.830 --> 00:28:57.300
that are a little bit less tested.

568
00:28:57.300 --> 00:29:00.420
Epididymitis, torsion,

569
00:29:00.420 --> 00:29:02.670
and a few other things on kidney stones.

570
00:29:02.670 --> 00:29:06.936
<v ->Thank you Dr. Gilmer.
(audience applauding)</v>

571
00:29:06.936 --> 00:29:09.603
(magical music)

